[  Kevin Indig shared this ](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/kevinindig%5Fwhere-do-consumers-go-when-they-finally-click-activity-7448327689691856896-4b2Q)  
Where do consumers go when they finally click out of an AI search result? Our latest 48-participant behavioral study indicates that when users leave AI Mode, they leave to buy, not to research. While 67% of standard search tasks involved visiting an external site to discover candidates, only 23% of AI Mode tasks triggered an external visit. The intent behind those clicks also fundamentally shifts: - In standard search, Users clicked on Reddit in 19% of tasks as users sought peer opinions. - In AI Mode, Reddit clicks happened in 8.8% of tasks. AI Mode users primarily clicked out to retailer sites, like Best Buy, or manufacturer pages to verify a price for a candidate they had already selected from the AI's list. This creates a heavily concentrated distribution of choices. For laptop queries, just three brands captured 93% of all AI Mode final choices. If a brand never appeared in the AI's initial output, participants simply never considered it. Visibility at the model layer isn't just a ranking metric; it is the new threshold for existing in the buyer's journey.  
