How do buyers decide which product to trust when they stop cross-checking multiple websites? In traditional search, the dominant trust mechanism is multi-source convergence. Users build confidence by triangulating information, checking to see if multiple independent sources agree on a product. This behavior occurred in 37% of the classic search tasks we analyzed. In AI Mode, that triangulation behavior drops to just 5%. Instead, trust relies heavily on two completely different signals: 1/ AI Framing (37%): Users trust the specific words and structure the AI uses to describe a product. 2/ Brand Recognition (34%): Users select or eliminate brands based on prior familiarity, regardless of the AI's description. When users lack an existing brand preference, the AI's framing becomes the deciding factor. For example, one participant chose an insurance provider simply because the AI surfaced an exact dollar amount rather than a percentage discount. In an AI-driven environment, the synthesis itself becomes the corroboration. Read the full study in this week's Growth Memo.  
