What happens to the comparison shopping phase when an AI model summarizes the options for you? It almost entirely disappears. Our recent usability study of 185 major-purchase tasks compared how users build shortlists in traditional Search versus AI Mode. The behavioral split is massive: - In classic search, 56% of participants built their own shortlist from scratch using multiple sources. - In AI Mode, 74% of final shortlists came directly from the AI's output with no external check. - Across all 149 AI Mode tasks, 64% of users clicked nothing at all. Instead of clicking through to review sites or retailer pages to evaluate options, users simply read the AI's text and declared their finalists. The comparison process didn't just shrink; for most participants, it didn't happen at all. When the search engine acts as a recommendation environment, buyers delegate the cognitive effort of comparison directly to the AI. Full breakdown in this week's Growth Memo.  
