AI Is Probabilistic, Random, & Measurable \* Key Takeaways: [https://lnkd.in/euw2ZgZk](https://lnkd.in/euw2ZgZk?trk=public%5Fprofile%5F%5Freactions-text)\* Full Paper: [https://lnkd.in/etTMdW5n](https://lnkd.in/etTMdW5n?trk=public%5Fprofile%5F%5Freactions-text)\* About: In this paper, [Gregory Druck](https://www.linkedin.com/in/gregory-druck-8977b825?trk=public%5Fprofile%5F%5Freactions-text), our Chief AI Officer, and I provide a comprehensive technical explanation of how LLM answers are generated, and we demonstrate that both visibility and ranking are measurable. We provide practical statistical frameworks, including confidence intervals, sequential sampling, and significance tests, so practitioners can measure both with appropriate precision, rather than guessing. Key Takeaways \* AI answers are not mysterious, inconsistent, or impractical to measure. Visibility and ranking can both be measured using well-established statistical tools like confidence intervals and probability distributions. \* The fact that the exact same set of entities rarely appears in the same order does not mean visibility and ranking are unmeasurable, or that we need a massive sample. \* The core model of LLMs deterministically creates probability distributions, which drive the generation of the next word, each with different probabilities. \* When RAG is used, it uses a search algorithm, which is largely deterministic. \* Answers are generated by sampling the probability distribution. Temperature and other components affect the randomness of the sample of the probability distribution. \* These probability distributions may not be visible to the end user, but this can be measured by running multiple runs of the same prompt. This is known in statistics as empirical sampling, which is a well-established measurement method. Incentives: We do not sell AI visibility tracking tools. We do sell AEO services. But we do not have a significant financial incentive to argue that AI visibility tracking is effective. Peer Review: Please disagree with and critique our research.  
